node.text:
This is a video by @namib_naude filmed on June 5. Naude and his fellow seal rescuers from @oceanconservationnamibia managed to disentangle 10 seal on that day. While this is great news, it's bittersweet as it means that we are by no means getting to the top of this major problem. This time of year is always bad, as now the young pups are starting to explore further and further offshore, picking up and playing with everything they find along the way. Most of the entanglements were very new, so no major damage to any of the animals yet. As soon as our national Lockdown is over, we need to have some serious chats with the local fishing industry.
.
.

How amazing it is to see these chubby beach pups getting rescued. We really appreciate what @oceanconservationnamibia is doing. This is one of the many videos of their seal rescue operations where they rescued 2 seal pups at a time. Here's how Naude Dreyer (@namib_naude) described this operation, "We saw 2 pups in the same group with entanglements, lying about 15 meters apart. The plan was that I would go for the 1 closer to the water by hand, while Antoine gets the other one in the net and leaves it. He then comes to help me and together we go to help the 2nd one afterwards. Sounds easy on paper but takes a bit of co-ordination and a lot of luck to pull off. Luckily it all went quite smoothly😊"
.
#sealrescue #animalrescue #oceanconservation #marineconservation #ocean_lovers_united

Naude Dreyer (@namib_naude) and his friend Antonie rescued this huge seal on February 26. This seal was so strong he dragged them both around and he didn’t actually fit into the net, that’s why they struggled so long to get him down! He had a very deeply embedded packing strap that must have caused immense pain. It's really amazing to see him getting rescued. Thanks to @oceanconservationnamibia .
📍#Namibia🇳🇦
.

By @namib_naude: Normally I wouldn’t take such a big animal alone, but didn’t want to let her get away either. Apologies for the loooong video, but I wanted to give everyone insight into how a rescue actually plays out. Usually they take over 5 minutes, and need to be edited shorter.
This line is the 3rd entanglement this year that I’ve felt a deliberate loop has been made and tossed in the ocean. Maybe to target seals? Who knows.
.
.
.

📹 @namib_naude: Must watch! This was hands down the biggest animal we've disentangled so far. He was probably around 90kg and very, very fiesty. He had some severe damage from a piece of trawler net, and could barely fit in our net. After a LOT of struggling and 2 attempts we managed to free the net finally. Even with 2 of us on the pole we could barely control him and you can see how he shook me off a few times. I feel that after the first time he got loose, he know what we were doing as he didn't run away, but allowed us to net him the second time. Took about 10 minutes to catch my breath again after this!

node.text:
A rare and beautiful capture of Migaloo, a well known brilliant white humpback whale. It was reportedly the only white albino whale in the world until an all white calf had been sighted just a few years ago. As humpbacks migrate annually to tropical waters to give birth, Migaloo and MJ (Migaloo junior) are a magical and rare encounter for avid whale watchers along Australia's East coast.
Image © Jenny Dean / via @discoverocean
